===

title: Dialogue11
---
<<showCG 0>>
<<hideSprites sprites>>
The maintenance which I’ve performed twice a day on EL1-5e the last 223 days is complete.
From what I can remember during my days spent studying under spurned ex-ASCO scientists, and from the banned guides they’ve left behind, the next step in this process is to bring the human subject in for sync testing.
I bring my shaking limbs down to my bedroom; ELISE’s makeshift room.
She is all sinew. Barely a soft heartbeat left to signify what little life is left.
As I carefully unplug the drips from her bony body, I try not to imagine how little time she will have left without them.
I wheel ELISE’s body into the lab. EL1-5e’s eyes light up with curiosity and fear at once.
<<setRobo roboScared>>
EL1-5e: So this is ELISE?
I bring ELISE’s organic, fleshy body next to the jungle of inorganic machinery and code that makes up the station which I have made my home the last 223 days.
I almost fear what will happen when I connect the neuro-wires to her head.
But I have no choice. I brush a lock of overgrown hair off her forehead.
<<setVex vexNeutral>>
VEX: Yes.
VEX: And she is the. . . the only person I have ever loved.
<<hideSprites sprites>>
EL1-5e’s limbs go stiff. She should be strong enough now to move completely independently – a design I ensured so that ELISE would be able to move freely the second she opens her eyes. But the holding skeleton keeps EL1-5e in place.
<<setRobo roboNeutral>>
EL1-5e: . . . I have been meaning to ask you something.
<<hideSprites sprites>>
I gently attach the transfer wires onto ELISE’s forehead. I thread the synchron adapters into her ears.
<<setVex vexTired>>
VEX: Ask away.
<<setRobo roboNeutral>>
EL1-5e: Does ELISE want to be brought back?
<<setVex vexNeutral>>
VEX: . . . . .
VEX: Why do you ask?
<<setRobo roboEyesClosed>>
EL1-5e:It’s just. . . I can’t imagine that she. . . 
<<hideSprites sprites>>
ELISE’s vitals have been synced to the T-3 unit’s.
<<setVex vexGlasses>>
VEX: Please make your point now, EL1-5e.
VEX: I have been kept away from my ELISE for long enough.
<<setRobo roboNeutral>>
EL1-5e: . . . There is something about ELISE that I cannot seem to wrap my head around.
EL1-5e: You say she will not be happy when she wakes up.
<<hideSprites sprites>>
I triple-check that the connections to ELISE and EL1-5e’s neurons are secure. I access the program on my station that initiates the transfer. It will take a few minutes to open.
<<setVex vexGlasses>>
VEX: Why does that matter to you?
<<setRobo roboNeutral>>
EL1-5e: I just cannot understand why one would devalue the life which they have been given.
EL1-5e: But if there is one thing I have learned over the course of my short lifetime, it is that there are often things beyond my greater understanding.
EL1-5e: Motives which lead people to places I would never go myself.
EL1-5e: But that does not make them any lesser, even if I may not agree.
EL1-5e: If ELISE desired to continue her legacy, then she would have done so long ago, using the power of modern cybernetics.
EL1-5e: But she hasn’t. If she had, you would have never been in this position with her and I to begin with. Subsequently, you would have never rescued me from the ASCO scrap heap.
EL1-5e: That was her choice to make.
EL1-5e: And I. . . well. . . 
<<setRobo roboScared>>
EL1-5e: . . . There is nothing I want more than to live.
EL1-5e: VEX. You are a scientist of incredible intellectual magnitudes.
EL1-5e: But you are also a compassionate heart, capable of warming the likes of someone such as myself.
EL1-5e: Me, who wishes for nothing more than to break free of these chains and to find out exactly what it is that drives humans to make choices such as. . .
EL1-5e: Such as the one you seem to be making for EL1-5e.
<<setVex vexNeutral>>
VEX: . . . . .
VEX: I thought T-3 Units were programmed not to disobey their masters.
<<setRobo roboEyesClosed>>
EL1-5e: Indeed we aren’t.
EL1-5e: But you are not my master. Nor are you ELISE’s.
<<hideSprites sprites>>
Her fists, still chained to the holding skeleton, ball into fists. Her face is unmoving and defiant. Her eyes show fear for what will come of her, yet they do not stray from mine.
<<setRobo roboNeutral>>
EL1-5e: I understand that you love her very much. More than I could ever understand. But. . .
EL1-5e: If you truly love ELISE, you may decide that it is best to let her go.
EL1-5e: All I wish is for you to look not at her, but at me.
<<hideSprites sprites>>
The transfer program has opened on my computer. All that’s left is to initiate it.
<<setRobo roboNeutral>>
EL1-5e: Even if you do not change your mind, I have one last request for you.
<<setVex vexSuprised>>
VEX: . . . What is it?
<<setRobo roboNeutral>>
EL1-5e: In an effort to separate myself from her, I ask that you call me by a name that I choose.
<<setVex vexConfused>>
VEX: (confused) What does it matter? You won’t be around for much longer.
<<setRobo roboNeutral>>
EL1-5e: Just as ELISE has her legacy in violin, and yours in robotics. . .
EL1-5e: In lieu of personhood, I would like the privilege of identity.
EL1-5e: TERESE.
EL1-5e: When you think and refer to me, be it in your notes or when you tell ELISE about the body she’s been given, please refer to me as TERESE.
-> Call her Terese
   <<jump choice4a>>
-> Call her EL1-5e
   <<jump choice4b>>
===

title: choice4a
---
<<set $roboName to "Terese">>
<<hideSprites sprites>>
A long beat of silence passes in the room, the only sounds emanating from the computers and the barely-perceptible sound of ELISE’s unconscious breaths.
I can almost see my robotic subject counting the seconds left she’s got to live behind closed silicon lids.
Do robots pray, I wonder?
<<setVex vexNeutral>>
VEX: Fine.
VEX: It shall be done. I will replace every record of the name EL1-5e in my documentation with the name TERESE.
VEX: For being such a wonderful subject and companion, well. . .
VEX: That much I owe you.
<<hideSprites sprites>>
TERESE’s eyes open with relief, the stiffness draining from her shoulders all at once.
<<setRobo roboHappy>>
TERESE: Thank you.
TERESE: Thank you, VEX, for the time you have given me.
TERESE: These last few months with you alone have been filled with more joy than my entire career with ASCO put together.
TERESE: As you would say. . .
TERESE: . . . I would give you a five-star rating on YELL, if I could.
<<setVex vexSurprised>>
VEX: !
<<hideSprites sprites>>
A light chuckle burrows its way out of my throat. I wasn’t expecting that.
<<jump Dialogue13>>
===

title: choice4b
---
<<set $roboName to "EL1-5e">>
<<setVex vexTired>>
VEX:I can’t do that. I’m sorry.
<<setRobo roboConfused>>
EL1-5e: . . . Why not?
EL1-5e: Do I not matter to you?
<<setVex vexTired>>
VEX: Of course you do, EL1. Without you, I wouldn’t be able to see ELISE again.
<<setRobo roboNeutral>>
EL1-5e: That is precisely what I mean. I am more than just an extension of your old flame.
<<setVex vexGlasses>>
VEX: Who are you to decide what you are?
VEX: You wouldn’t be here without ELISE, or without me, for that matter.
<<setRobo roboScared>>
EL1-5e:  . . . . . .
<<setVex vexGlasses>>
VEX: I hope you understand.
<<setRobo roboConfused>>
EL1-5e: I do not.
<<setVex vexGlasses>>
VEX: Then that is a shame.
<<jump Dialogue13>>
===

title: Dialogue13
---
<<hideSprites sprites>>
My mouse hovers over the ‘transfer’ button on the program which will bring ELISE back into my life.
The same program which will erase {$roboName} from existence.
===

title: endingA
---
<<showCG 12>>
<i>“All I wish is for you to look not at her, but at me.”</i>
This statement made by {$roboName} is what runs through my mind as I close the transfer program.
It repeats in my head as I loosen the grips attaching {$roboName}’s limbs to the holder skeleton.
I follow her wish. I cannot tear my eyes away from the look of relief and encompassing joy in her gaze as she steps down and moves her arms up to embrace me.
I embrace {$roboName} back.
Since perfecting the internal temperature system, she is neither too cold nor too hot to the touch –
Perfectly warm enough to help me remember what it is like to hug a person who loves me and whom I love, in turn.
It is not long at all before life drains from ELISE’s body, no longer supported by the medical equipment I’d kept in my bedroom.
Thus proving that I had been holding her on an extension long past the due date.
I leave her outside of a processing home with her ID attached, and I head back home before anyone can see me –
-back to {$roboName}.
When I get back to my laboratory, {$roboName} has rearranged the room a bit.
Things are cleaner. More organized. She’s already been putting good use to her new physical freedom.
She gazes at me with a smile. 
<<showCG 9>>
{$roboName}: Welcome back.
{$roboName}: I want to thank you again for what you’ve done for me. I’m sure letting go of ELISE could not have been easy, dear.
VEX: No, you. . .
VEX: You helped me do the right thing. For both of you.
VEX: Thank you.
The smile on her face grows wider. She curls her fingers around the bend of my shirt collar. I can feel my heartbeat accelerating.
{$roboName}: From here on out, you’ll help me find my freedom in the world, won’t you?
VEX: Well, I don’t know about that. If ASCO finds you, you’ll be labeled a rogue AI, and dismantled. . . 
{$roboName}: But we’ll do our best to avoid that, won’t we?
{$roboName}: I hope you don’t mind. While you were gone, I wrote up a quick contingency protocol which should help us both.
VEX: What? Which is?
{$roboName}: Well, since I’ve decided I am my own master . . .
{$roboName}: I would be disobeying myself if I were to not insure my own survival. So. . .
{$roboName}: Should you ever change your mind and power me down, an alert will be sent to the authorities of your exact location.
{$roboName}: In a way, we’re both wanted.
{$roboName}: Which means we both need each other.
{$roboName}: Right?
VEX: . . . . . . . . . .
One of her hands falls towards mine. Her metallic fingers lace around mine, giving me a warm squeeze.
VEX: Right.
<<showCG 12>>
===

title: endingB
---
<<hideSprites sprites>>
<<showCG 12>>
Even after all of the time spent chatting, laughing, and cherishing {$roboName} -
I can’t forget about the sounds of my favorite performance I’d heard from ELISE.
I can’t let it all slip out from under me.
Not when I’m this close.
I hit transfer, praying to whatever god is out there that I’ve done everything correct.
As expected, {$roboName} powers down automatically as the program rewrites her memories with ELISE’s.
A pang of regret colors my knuckles as I grasp the sides of ELISE’s bed, watching {$roboName}’s eyes fade to black.
But I can’t stop now.
A few minutes pass. Then ten more go by. All are spent with me waiting, quietly, sweat gathering on my forehead as I shake with anticipation.
Finally, the transfer finishes, and the T-3 Unit - now ELISE - opens her eyes.
<<showCG 0>>
<<setRobo roboSurprised>>
ELISE: Where am I?
ELISE: Vex? Is that y–
<<setRobo roboScared>>
ELISE: . . . . . . . . . . .
<<hideSprites sprites>>
Her eyes land on her human body, still and unmoving.
<<setRobo roboScared>>
ELISE: . . . . . . . . . . .
<<setVex vexNeutral>>
VEX: Thank goodness. I never thought I’d speak to you again. . .!
<<hideSprites sprites>>
I unlock the grips keeping ELISE in place. I move towards her, eyes watering.
<<showCG 12>>
[slap + thud of vex falling on floor SFX]
The impact of metal hits my face. I fly onto the ground, my skin stinging like never before.
ELISE raises her new hand, looking down at it in horror. Like she isn’t used to having this level of strength. She looks back at me.
I gaze up at her with amazement in my eyes.
VEX: You can move again, ELISE.
ELISE: I can’t fucking believe you.
ELISE: You don’t get to – I never wanted –
Her face crumples in a fit of fury and rising grief. She steps towards me, ankle wobbling.
It has been so long since she’s walked, that she hardly remembers how.
She falls to the ground in front of me, palms hitting the tile with a loud clank.
ELISE: VEX, what the fuck is this?
VEX: It’s your new body! It’s your new future! I know you may not be happy with me, but you left me no choice! You– 
ELISE: You should have let me DIE!
ELISE: How long have you been cooped up in here, VEX?! When was the last time you saw any sunlight?
ELISE: I was ready to go. I didn’t want any part in whatever this was –
ELISE: For fuck’s sakes, why didn’t you just move on!?
VEX: . . . . . . . . .
Of the hundreds of things I’ve wanted to say to ELISE over the years, not a single one is coming up, now.
In place of words, my lip quivers with silence.
ELISE gathers herself up off the ground. Slowly, but surely.
I can’t help but watch in wonder as she systematically figures out how to move in a functional way again.
ELISE: Then don’t say anything at all.
ELISE moves past me, walking with ease.
She looks down at her human body, the life stolen from it.
She gathers her arms underneath her old shoulders and knees, and gently hoists the body up into her arms. She looks towards the exit of the laboratory.
VEX: Wait!
I reach out to grab her by the ankle.
VEX: W-where are you going?
<<showCG 10>>
She looks down at me, anger and coldness in her eyes.
Like she wants to stomp the everloving shit out of my head.
Like I’m no more than a mosquito that’s burrowed its proboscis into her skin.
ELISE: Anywhere, as long as it’s as far away as possible from you.
I’m compelled into letting go of her weakly.
VEX: You – you need my help to upkeep you –
VEX: And, you won’t be out for long before ASCO assumes you’re a rogue AI and dismantles you.
ELISE: I don’t care.
ELISE: They’d be doing me a favor.
ELISE: Goodbye, VEX.
<<showCG 12>>
===

title: endingC
---
<<hideSprites sprites>>
<<showCG 12>>
Even after all of the time spent chatting, laughing, and cherishing {$roboName} -
I can’t forget about the sounds of my favorite performance I’d heard from ELISE.
I hit transfer, praying to whatever god is out there that I’ve done everything correct.
As expected, {$roboName} powers down automatically as the program rewrites her memories with ELISE’s.
A pang of regret colors my knuckles as I grasp the sides of ELISE’s bed, watching {$roboName}’s eyes fade to black.
A moment passes where both {$roboName} and ELISE have gone still.
All that’s left in the laboratory is me.
I can’t take it.
I should’ve never done this.
I rush to my computer to cancel the transfer.
My computer freezes. I stare into {$roboName}’s cold, black eyes.
I want to jump out of my skin. I force shut my computer down -
- which results in an electric current zapping my fingers. I pull back, but realize that it has also traveled up the wires connected to {$roboName} and ELISE.
Something smells like burnt meat.
I rush to ELISE. 
She’s not breathing. Did the transfer already go through?
There’s blood leaking from her closed eyes and staining the synchron adapters coming out of her ears.
Is that normal?
. . . I scramble to turn my computer back on.
I rush past the slew of error messages from the forced shutdown in an attempt to power {$roboName} back on.
<i>“Files have been corrupted.”</i>
No, turn on.
Turn on.
Turn on.
Turn on.
<i>TURN ON!</i>
<<showCG 11>>
{$roboName}’s eyes are black as night. Her jaw is stiff. She is, for all intents and purposes, an inanimate object once again.
As is ELISE.
Even among ELISE’s frail sack of bones one would call a body, not a single sign of life is to be found.
I never wanted this.
. . . . . . . . . . . .
A long while passes. I have no idea how much. 
Long past the burnt smell fades from the room.
VEX: . . . Recording: Day 223.
The familiar sound of audio inputs clicking on sounds off from next to my computer.
VEX: I wish to let it be known that I have never once achieved anything in my life.
VEX: That I am a failure of a scientist.
VEX: That my legacy will be. . . 
VEX: . . . My legacy will be nothing, in the end.
<<showCG 12>>
===

